00:54:32,240 --> 00:54:35,300
Scott: Sort of like the same one that's in a Game Boy Color on the front, right?

791
00:54:35,961 --> 00:54:47,480
Scott: And it detects when infrared light blinks at it in a certain pattern, and then the TV behaves according to whatever, so if it received the blinking pattern, sort of like a Morse code you could think of it as, right?

792
00:54:47,920 --> 00:54:49,989
Scott: For volume up, the TV turns its volume up.

793
00:54:50,250 --> 00:54:52,400
Scott: If it received the signal from volume down, it goes down, right?

794
00:54:53,121 --> 00:54:56,600
Scott: The problem was that every TV decided on different signals for the different buttons.

795
00:54:57,000 --> 00:54:59,660
Scott: Different TVs had different buttons on their remotes, right?

796
00:54:59,920 --> 00:55:01,995
Scott: So then you had VCRs getting in the picture, right?

797
00:55:03,340 --> 00:55:12,800
Rym: Sometimes you'd have a TV that would detect the wrong signals, like if you had two TVs in your house, one of them would partially fuck with the other TV, but not in a reliable way.

798
00:55:12,820 --> 00:55:14,669
Rym: If they were next to each other, right?

799
00:55:14,809 --> 00:55:17,120
Scott: If you had line of sight to both TVs from where you were sitting.

800
00:55:17,620 --> 00:55:17,680
Rym: Yep.

801
00:55:17,700 --> 00:55:30,860
Rym: We had a giant mirror in our kitchen, or in our dining room/kitchen area, and another giant mirror opposite it in a different room in the living room, and you could basically work the remote from almost anywhere in the house because of that.

802
00:55:31,821 --> 00:55:32,583
Scott: Yeah, that'll do it.

803
00:55:32,684 --> 00:55:34,310
Scott: I mean, infrared light is just light.

804
00:55:34,792 --> 00:55:37,060
Scott: You can't see it because you have stupid shitty human eyeballs.

805
00:55:37,360 --> 00:55:39,271
Scott: If you put on night vision goggles, you can see it.

806
00:55:39,292 --> 00:55:40,680
Scott: It's just a light bulb blinking.

807
00:55:41,620 --> 00:55:41,701
Rym: Yeah.

808
00:55:41,782 --> 00:55:42,732
Rym: In fact, I remember as a kid...

809
00:55:43,420 --> 00:55:45,527
Scott: We could have used actual light bulbs to do this.

810
00:55:45,547 --> 00:55:49,240
Scott: We didn't need to use infrared ones, but infrared ones were just better.

811
00:55:49,601 --> 00:55:50,940
Rym: When I was a kid, I learned it was infrared.

812
00:55:51,080 --> 00:55:52,560
Scott: You don't bother people by blinking.

813
00:55:53,562 --> 00:55:58,472
Rym: We had this simple thermometer that was like a strip of almost film strip.

814
00:55:58,492 --> 00:56:02,780
Rym: You hold it up to your forehead, and it would turn colors, and it was basically like a very simple thermometer.

815
00:56:03,341 --> 00:56:08,757
Rym: But if you just held it in front of a remote control, and hit the power button and a bunch of buttons, it would basically show a fever.

816
00:56:10,660 --> 00:56:17,260
Rym: So, you could point the remote control at this thing, make it show a fever, then hold it on your head, and then show your parents that you had a fever in school.

817
00:56:17,782 --> 00:56:22,140
Rym: That worked exactly zero times because my parents figured out exactly what I was doing.

818
00:56:23,042 --> 00:56:24,859
Scott: Well, they can just touch your head and be like, "This makes no

819
00:56:24,879 --> 00:56:24,980
Scott: sense.".

820
00:56:24,980 --> 00:56:27,331
Rym: Yeah, they were like, "Eh, let's use the real thermometer.

821
00:56:27,351 --> 00:56:27,411
Rym: Huh.

822
00:56:28,034 --> 00:56:28,617
Rym: No fever.

823
00:56:28,637 --> 00:56:28,697
Rym: Huh.".

824
00:56:29,380 --> 00:56:32,614
Rym: And you have the remote control in your bed for some reason.

825
00:56:33,056 --> 00:56:33,920
Rym: That's where it went.

826
00:56:34,880 --> 00:56:35,001
Scott: Okay.

827
00:56:36,230 --> 00:56:37,720
Scott: Yeah, losing the remote became a thing.

828
00:56:37,780 --> 00:56:47,860
Scott: But this technology for remote controlling the TV was somewhat actually slowly, but at least from my perspective, applied to other things.

829
00:56:48,240 --> 00:56:51,708
Scott: I have a remote control fan over here.

830
00:56:51,728 --> 00:56:56,480
Scott: Remote control lights in your house are still not common.

831
00:56:57,800 --> 00:57:02,460
Rym: Bit by bit, there was a boom of a lot of things started to have their own remote controls that were all proprietary.

832
00:57:03,060 --> 00:57:06,275
Rym: But then bit by bit, there was just too much proliferation.

833
00:57:06,316 --> 00:57:07,240
Rym: People didn't care that much.

834
00:57:07,240 --> 00:57:08,847
Scott: I guess it doesn't make sense to have a remote control.

835
00:57:08,928 --> 00:57:11,500
Scott: It's like you really need a microwave for the remote control, right?

836
00:57:12,744 --> 00:57:16,100
Rym: Only if I could somehow have the microwave go get the food and put it in itself.

837
00:57:17,280 --> 00:57:17,420
Scott: Right.

838
00:57:17,521 --> 00:57:25,240
Scott: It's like you could remote control basically any electronic device, but you need a good reason to do that.

839
00:57:25,580 --> 00:57:27,444
Scott: You've got car remote door openers.

840
00:57:28,145 --> 00:57:35,100
Scott: Those are not infrared because your car might be far away from where you are and not have line of sight to it.

841
00:57:35,441 --> 00:57:43,280
Rym: But the thing about remote controls is that all these early remote controls had zero security whatsoever because it didn't seem like it mattered.

842
00:57:43,901 --> 00:57:47,955
Rym: Someone can change the channel on your television, okay?

843
00:57:48,497 --> 00:57:49,240
Rym: That's what it's for.

844
00:57:49,780 --> 00:57:53,651
Rym: You can occasionally prank people by changing the channel through their window.

845
00:57:53,692 --> 00:57:56,420
Rym: if you knew what kind of TV they had and you had a remote that would work.

846
00:57:57,240 --> 00:58:03,940
Rym: But garage door openers became a big problem because I remember in the 80s and early 90s, a lot of them used a very small number of codes.

847
00:58:04,341 --> 00:58:11,060
Rym: And it was very common for one person to have a garage door opener that would open like three other random garages in the neighborhood.

848
00:58:11,940 --> 00:58:12,040
Scott: Yeah.

849
00:58:12,060 --> 00:58:21,440
Scott: If you open up, I guess, I don't know how the newer ones work, but like just any garage door opener or remote car door opener, unlocker thing, you open them up.

850
00:58:21,500 --> 00:58:26,280
Scott: And basically what you'll see is there's going to be a little set of dip switches, right?

851
00:58:26,841 --> 00:58:29,209
Scott: And you know, there'll be, I don't know how many, right?

852
00:58:29,290 --> 00:58:31,257
Scott: But you only, if you have like, you got to think, right?

853
00:58:31,477 --> 00:58:32,220
Scott: They're all binary.

854
00:58:32,781 --> 00:58:39,859
Scott: So if you got like eight switches, that's like, you know, what, two to the eighth or whatever, eight, I don't forget the binary, two to the eighth or eight squared, I don't know.

855
00:58:40,941 --> 00:58:46,057
Scott: My math is bad right now in binary, but you got, there's a lot of possible combinations, right?

856
00:58:46,077 --> 00:58:47,867
Rym: So the odds of you conflicting- Don't you just want a factorial?

857
00:58:47,928 --> 00:58:49,440
Rym: I guess it depends on the symmetry.

858
00:58:50,461 --> 00:58:51,404
Scott: It's just binary, right?

859
00:58:51,444 --> 00:58:55,460
Scott: It's like, if you've got eight, eight bits is how many possible combinations, right?

860
00:58:55,921 --> 00:59:01,560
Rym: Of course, the real problem was they were, you, all these early remote controls used fixed codes.

861
00:59:02,200 --> 00:59:07,400
Rym: They use like, this is the signal that will open this garage door all the time.

862
00:59:08,302 --> 00:59:14,840
Scott: The idea was that you would ship them with, you know, a different, you know, you'd key in a different one at the factory on to each one.

863
00:59:15,140 --> 00:59:18,500
Scott: So the, you know, two people buy one from the same hardware store, they won't get the same code.

864
00:59:19,141 --> 00:59:25,526
Scott: But I remember the one my grandparents had, because we didn't have a garage, but the one my grandparents had, the actual dip switches were exposed.

865
00:59:26,067 --> 00:59:34,920
Scott: So if you could find someone in the neighborhood, you obviously had to remember your little, your dip switch configuration or else you wouldn't be able to open your own garage door.

866
00:59:37,143 --> 00:59:41,040
Scott: But I guess if you had the key, you could get into the garage and re-figure it out, right?

867
00:59:41,080 --> 00:59:47,920
Scott: But you could go around the neighborhood and flick the switches and try to open up other people's garage doors if they had the same garage door opener.

868
00:59:48,221 --> 00:59:57,580
Rym: I guess it's just interesting that even in these early days, there was proto, like not internet of things, but it was suddenly we have remote access to things to control them.

869
00:59:58,181 --> 01:00:01,620
Rym: And nobody put even the barest thought into security at first.

870
01:00:01,860 --> 01:00:03,940
Scott: They put the barest thought, they figured that that would be good enough.

871
01:00:04,000 --> 01:00:08,540
Scott: What are the odds that two people are going to pick the same code and have the same garage door opener in the same place?

872
01:00:08,740 --> 01:00:14,360
Rym: Yeah, but what they didn't think about is a nefarious actor who would just, like you could pretty easily try a lot of combinations.

873
01:00:14,701 --> 01:00:19,320
Scott: What are the odds that two people have the same garage door opener in the same neighborhood with the same evil, right?

874
01:00:19,580 --> 01:00:25,860
Rym: Yeah, except in my, in practice, like in my own life, it happened constantly everywhere I ever lived due to the density of houses.

875
01:00:26,680 --> 01:00:26,780
Scott: Yeah.

876
01:00:26,840 --> 01:00:40,200
Scott: Well also people wouldn't, you know, in those days it would have been very much more difficult to say it would be easy to do this now, but to just make a computerized radio that attempts to open every possible garage door opener brand with every possible code.

877
01:00:40,581 --> 01:00:44,458
Scott: So you just go up to any garage, they have this actually, the TV be gone, right?

878
01:00:44,498 --> 01:00:44,840
Scott: That thing?

879
01:00:45,420 --> 01:00:58,660
Scott: It's like you just push it and aim it at a TV in like a bar and it tries to tell it to turn off using every infrared pattern for every major television brand and you wait a while, eventually it'll turn that TV off.

880
01:00:58,760 --> 01:01:02,620
Scott: Sooner or later it'll find the right code to get that TV to turn itself off.

881
01:01:02,720 --> 01:01:02,921
Scott: Yup.

882
01:01:03,562 --> 01:01:07,249
Rym: And there's really no way to see, like there's no point in securing something like that.

883
01:01:07,309 --> 01:01:12,860
Rym: Like put a piece of tape over it and don't use the remote if you actually care about like the security of controlling that TV.

884
01:01:13,520 --> 01:01:13,620
Scott: Right.

885
01:01:13,820 --> 01:01:14,261
Scott: Exactly.

886
01:01:14,301 --> 01:01:18,548
Scott: So, you know, garage door opener, it's like you would need like a radio on whatever frequency it is, right?

887
01:01:18,568 --> 01:01:20,150
Scott: Some whatever megahertz, right?

888
01:01:20,170 --> 01:01:26,340
Scott: That's broadcasting every possible signal to get garage doors to open in a sequence really fast.

889
01:01:27,201 --> 01:01:28,424
Scott: As fast as you can, right?

890
01:01:28,444 --> 01:01:30,270
Scott: Because you can't do it super fast.

891
01:01:30,290 --> 01:01:31,653
Scott: You have to do one after the other, right?

892
01:01:31,673 --> 01:01:33,980
Scott: Because if you mix them together, well, they just interfere with each other.

893
01:01:34,440 --> 01:01:34,721
Rym: Right.

894
01:01:34,741 --> 01:01:43,620
Rym: But I guess the other interesting thing that happened with like remote controls, especially on TVs, is that it opened up a secondary market that previously hadn't existed.

895
01:01:44,320 --> 01:01:52,520
Rym: Like for third parties to, one, people would like buy and sell old remotes, like have an extra remote could be useful if you lost yours or you broke it or something.

896
01:01:52,961 --> 01:01:59,460
Rym: But two, people started making generic remote controls, universal remote controls, and configurable remote controls.

897
01:02:00,100 --> 01:02:00,200
Scott: Right.

898
01:02:00,220 --> 01:02:03,831
Scott: Well, because it's like even though the patterns were different on every device, right?

899
01:02:03,871 --> 01:02:06,057
Scott: People, A, had two problems they wanted to solve, right?

900
01:02:07,320 --> 01:02:10,147
Scott: Problem one, my remote is lost or broken.

901
01:02:10,167 --> 01:02:11,409
Scott: I can't get the original one.

902
01:02:11,429 --> 01:02:13,213
Scott: Maybe it's not even possible to get it anymore.

903
01:02:13,654 --> 01:02:16,020
Scott: I'll just buy this remote that works with any possible TV.

904
01:02:16,821 --> 01:02:20,869
Scott: And it has in it programmed all the patterns for all the TVs.

905
01:02:20,929 --> 01:02:26,979
Scott: because the person who made this remote collected a bunch of remotes and wrote down all the signals, right?

906
01:02:27,440 --> 01:02:28,324
Rym: It's easy to figure out.

907
01:02:28,344 --> 01:02:31,658
Rym: You hit a button, see what signal comes out, hit another button, see what signal comes out.

908
01:02:31,678 --> 01:02:32,120
Rym: Like that's it.

909
01:02:32,240 --> 01:02:32,701
Scott: Exactly.

910
01:02:32,821 --> 01:02:38,453
Scott: You're like, okay, volume up on the Samsung TV is two and volume down is three.

911
01:02:38,573 --> 01:02:41,720
Scott: On the Magnavox TV, up is four and down is five, right?

912
01:02:41,820 --> 01:02:50,614
Scott: So you just need to put all that in the memory of one little circuit on your remote and people type in a number.

913
01:02:50,874 --> 01:02:54,340
Scott: In the book, you would say type in this number for this TV brand and poof, there you go.

914
01:02:55,940 --> 01:02:58,583
Scott: The remote is now doing what your original remote would do.

915
01:02:58,963 --> 01:03:06,870
Scott: But also, people had VCRs and cable boxes back in the day and those had their own remotes.

916
01:03:06,990 --> 01:03:08,994
Scott: You'd have three remotes and it was a pain in the ass.

917
01:03:09,054 --> 01:03:18,790
Scott: But theoretically, if you set everything up right, there was a way to do it where you could have the cable box or usually the VCR remote would be like the best one.

918
01:03:18,950 --> 01:03:19,211
Rym: Yep.

919
01:03:19,291 --> 01:03:23,830
Rym: The VCR remote was the one that had all the buttons you needed to control the other devices eventually.

920
01:03:23,910 --> 01:03:37,610
Scott: So if you wired it up wisely and everything worked together and cleverly, you could make it such to where the VCR remote would, via the VCR, control the other devices.

921
01:03:37,830 --> 01:03:46,550
Scott: You would turn the VCR on, the TV and the cable box would then turn on on their own because they were plugged into the VCR or into each other and then into the VCR.

922
01:03:47,091 --> 01:03:49,677
Scott: And then you would change channels on the VCR.

923
01:03:49,697 --> 01:03:55,310
Scott: The TV would be stuck on channel 3 but the cable would go into the VCR which would then go to the TV.

924
01:03:56,650 --> 01:04:03,230
Scott: And so when you change channels on the VCR, the TV channel would be changing because the VCR is converting it to channel 3.

925
01:04:03,230 --> 01:04:06,276
Scott: And then if you played a movie on the VCR, it's like alright, you're playing a movie now.

926
01:04:06,757 --> 01:04:08,321
Scott: Just ignore whatever the cable box is doing.

927
01:04:09,002 --> 01:04:12,910
Scott: You could just use that VCR remote for everything if you did it right and almost no one did it right.

928
01:04:13,471 --> 01:04:19,126
Rym: Yep, we had our system set up very tightly in my house but we watched a lot of TV and that was very important to us.

929
01:04:19,146 --> 01:04:20,610
Rym: so we spent a lot of time making everything work.

930
01:04:22,911 --> 01:04:30,850
Scott: But yeah, so what you'd end up doing is you'd get this universal remote that would instead be able to control all the different devices and switch between them.

931
01:04:30,950 --> 01:04:37,130
Scott: You'd push a button on it for VCR and now this one remote is the VCR remote and it's more convenient than having three things on your lap.

932
01:04:37,530 --> 01:04:42,530
Scott: You have one thing and you just have to push buttons on it to transform it into the different remotes.

933
01:04:42,530 --> 01:04:50,550
Rym: I remember as a kid, in that era, the only people who had a system that was overcomplicated and didn't work were the people who also had a fancy surround system.

934
01:04:52,270 --> 01:04:59,570
Scott: Yeah, it's hard to get, people who didn't think about it and didn't understand wouldn't set it up the way it was intended and make things difficult for themselves.

935
01:05:00,451 --> 01:05:10,687
Scott: If you knew how it worked and you thought about it, you would somehow use your receiver for your surround system as the central control for your whole everything.

936
01:05:13,831 --> 01:05:24,230
Scott: The problem was that if you did that, it meant that every time you watch TV, you're using surround sound and some people, like in my house, you wouldn't always want the surround sound on, it's loud.

937
01:05:26,352 --> 01:05:29,200
Scott: In my apartment, I always have it on, but it's not that loud.

938
01:05:29,260 --> 01:05:31,306
Scott: Back in the day, that was loud.

939
01:05:31,366 --> 01:05:32,530
Scott: It would wake up the whole house.

940
01:05:33,630 --> 01:05:35,216
Rym: So I just learned something fascinating.

941
01:05:35,276 --> 01:05:39,690
Rym: I did not realize this was ever used in consumer technology, but apparently in the early 80s it was common.

942
01:05:40,470 --> 01:05:45,466
Rym: A lot of remote controls in that era, when we were growing up, were not IR.

943
01:05:45,486 --> 01:05:46,590
Rym: They were ultrasonic.

944
01:05:47,791 --> 01:05:48,090
Scott: Interesting.

945
01:05:48,270 --> 01:05:53,130
Rym: And they were extremely prone to failure and extremely prone to false signals.

946
01:05:54,060 --> 01:05:54,269
Scott: Yes.

947
01:05:54,810 --> 01:05:55,710
Rym: For all the reasons you can imagine.

948
01:05:55,730 --> 01:05:59,370
Scott: I think it was in fact a few really old TVs that had like a wired remote that was like...

949
01:05:59,450 --> 01:06:00,174
Rym: Oh, I had one of those.

950
01:06:00,214 --> 01:06:02,990
Rym: My first VCR had a wired remote to the VCR.

951
01:06:03,910 --> 01:06:03,977
Scott: Mmm.

952
01:06:04,551 --> 01:06:06,363
Rym: Plug it into a slot and it was a wire.

953
01:06:06,383 --> 01:06:07,350
Rym: It was like 10 feet long.

954
01:06:08,091 --> 01:06:10,990
Scott: It seems ancient when you think about it, but how is it different from a gamepad?

955
01:06:11,530 --> 01:06:11,621
Rym: Yeah.

956
01:06:12,530 --> 01:06:14,677
Rym: Wireless controllers on video game consoles?

957
01:06:15,379 --> 01:06:19,050
Rym: Not common and didn't work well for a long time.

958
01:06:19,552 --> 01:06:22,327
Scott: The first ones that were really wireless were what?

959
01:06:22,367 --> 01:06:22,950
Scott: Like Xbox?

960
01:06:23,230 --> 01:06:25,210
Rym: Well, I mean Atari had a wireless controller.

961
01:06:26,030 --> 01:06:27,165
Scott: Yeah, but yeah, so did NES.

962
01:06:28,130 --> 01:06:29,115
Scott: But it's like they were Garbo, right?

963
01:06:29,155 --> 01:06:31,970
Scott: The first ones that were any good were Xbox 360, I want to say.

964
01:06:32,450 --> 01:06:34,770
Rym: Yeah, the first ones that were good, that just worked?

965
01:06:35,130 --> 01:06:36,297
Scott: PS2 wasn't wireless.

966
01:06:36,337 --> 01:06:36,759
Scott: I guess PS3 was?

967
01:06:36,779 --> 01:06:36,880
Scott: Right?

968
01:06:39,550 --> 01:06:43,027
Scott: I want to say PS3, Xbox 360 was like... and Wii.

969
01:06:43,108 --> 01:06:43,530
Scott: Wiimotes.

970
01:06:44,873 --> 01:06:48,070
Scott: Because GameCube remotes were not... well, there was the GameCube Air one.

971
01:06:49,416 --> 01:06:50,628
Scott: That was one of the first ones also.

972
01:06:51,270 --> 01:07:03,810
Rym: But it's interesting how the change in both controllers becoming wireless and TVs becoming larger and higher resolution changed how people interact with TVs as well when they're playing games.

973
01:07:04,230 --> 01:07:17,590
Rym: Because when we were young, even young as late as like the Super Nintendo or the N64 or the PlayStation 1, you'd have to sit really close to your TV to play anything because the cords were not long on those controllers.

974
01:07:17,891 --> 01:07:20,150
Scott: You'd also be changing cartridges and stuff.

975
01:07:20,450 --> 01:07:21,789
Rym: Yep, there was no remote control for that.

976
01:07:21,990 --> 01:07:29,710
Scott: If you had a wireless NES remote and you wanted to change games, you're getting up to swap the cartridge or the disc on your GameCube even if it wave-birded, right?

977
01:07:30,030 --> 01:07:36,886
Scott: So it wasn't the fact of digital games just opening on the menu and changing games like on the Xbox 360 or the PS3, right?

978
01:07:38,691 --> 01:07:43,148
Scott: Now the wireless controller made way more sense because you didn't have to get up ever, right?

979
01:07:43,188 --> 01:07:43,670
Scott: Basically.

980
01:07:43,930 --> 01:08:02,470
Rym: And now you're at the point where like a Nintendo Switch and its dock, any of the controllers, if they're first party, are also sort of a remote control and you can turn on the Switch from the controller wherever you are and that will, if your TV isn't too ancient, automatically turn on the TV and set it to whatever HDMI input.

981
01:08:03,390 --> 01:08:06,409
Scott: Yeah, if you've got everything configured that way, then sure, it totally works.

982
01:08:06,571 --> 01:08:09,390
Rym: Yeah, that should just be automatic on any current setup.

983
01:08:10,570 --> 01:08:12,378
Scott: You know, you might have a setup where you don't want to do that.

984
01:08:12,398 --> 01:08:14,830
Scott: Maybe you've got some other in-between device, something going on.

985
01:08:15,131 --> 01:08:17,750
Scott: But yeah, I think for most people, that's what you would want to do.

986
01:08:17,890 --> 01:08:24,569
Rym: The other thing I learned, because we were just talking about how it changed the way people interacted with media because they could change channels, like channel surfing became a thing.

987
01:08:25,430 --> 01:08:34,109
Rym: Apparently in 1952, a product was sold that was a wireless remote called the Blaboff in the United States and its sole purpose, it was just a mute button.

988
01:08:34,752 --> 01:08:35,674
Rym: And it was marketed.

989
01:08:35,975 --> 01:08:40,808
Rym: as any time the ad read happens, the Blaboff will make sure you don't have to hear it.

990
01:08:42,710 --> 01:08:51,050
Rym: So there is some very Rym or Scott-like personality has been thinking about how to use this technology for good from the very beginning.

991
01:08:52,210 --> 01:08:58,390
Scott: Well, I mean, you've also got to think one of the best things about remote controls is just what they've done for accessibility, right?

992
01:08:58,410 --> 01:09:01,278
Scott: There's a famous old TV commercial, the clapper, right?

993
01:09:01,359 --> 01:09:05,310
Scott: And it was always sort of like a joke, like clap on, clap off the clapper.

994
01:09:05,410 --> 01:09:06,974
Scott: But the clapper lets you turn your lights.

995
01:09:07,113 --> 01:09:09,099
Scott: It was basically what you would do with this thing.

996
01:09:09,560 --> 01:09:13,670
Scott: is you plug it into your power outlet and then you would plug your lights into the clapper, right?

997
01:09:13,750 --> 01:09:17,090
Scott: It basically just went into your power outlet between whatever device.

998
01:09:18,050 --> 01:09:19,790
Rym: Really simplistic, this thing, how it works.

999
01:09:19,870 --> 01:09:23,055
Scott: If it hears clapping noises, right?

1000
01:09:23,115 --> 01:09:32,310
Scott: Sometimes erroneously, sometimes not sensitive enough, it wasn't perfect, but it would just cut power or allow power to go back on.

1001
01:09:32,911 --> 01:09:35,276
Scott: So you could turn your lights on and off from bed, right?

1002
01:09:35,336 --> 01:09:41,270
Scott: Or turn your TV on and off just by clapping, even if it wasn't a remote control TV or usually your lights.

1003
01:09:41,850 --> 01:09:48,270
Scott: And what this was, you know, for normal people seems kind of seemed a little bit silly, but you know, it's like, okay, it's not too bad, right?

1004
01:09:48,270 --> 01:09:56,030
Scott: It's like I turn the lights on when I entered the bedroom with the switch that's right near the door, I get in bed, then I clap and I turn the lights off because the switch is all the way over there.

1005
01:09:56,451 --> 01:09:58,767
Scott: Now I don't have to make a trip in the dark to my bed, right?

1006
01:09:58,807 --> 01:09:59,230
Scott: From the door.

1007
01:09:59,490 --> 01:10:09,330
Rym: It illustrates that concept that good user experience design often automatically becomes good or at least acceptable accessibility design.

1008
01:10:10,050 --> 01:10:10,190
Scott: Right.

1009
01:10:10,210 --> 01:10:17,530
Scott: Well, what if you are a senior person or a person who has a hard time walking or, you know, someone who could trip and fall in the dark and severely hurt themselves, right?

1010
01:10:17,630 --> 01:10:25,730
Scott: This silly thing suddenly becomes like this, you know, life saving, changing type device, you know, some, you know, if you have a hard time getting up, right.

1011
01:10:25,850 --> 01:10:29,370
Scott: It's like you want to change to control the channel on the TV and it's a dial.

1012
01:10:30,090 --> 01:10:34,050
Scott: It's like you're going to, you know, an old an old person who can barely walk like a walker.

1013
01:10:34,310 --> 01:10:38,450
Scott: Imagine them getting up to walk over to the TV, turn a dial, then go sit down again every time.

1014
01:10:38,610 --> 01:10:41,201
Scott: It's like, you know, versus remote control.

1015
01:10:41,281 --> 01:10:43,290
Scott: It's like that's that's life saving.

1016
01:10:43,571 --> 01:10:52,830
Rym: The clapper also, as an aside, in terms of usability, very pointedly notice that remote controls for lights have never been common or popular for a lot of reasons.

1017
01:10:53,190 --> 01:10:57,110
Rym: The main reason is you would have to carry that remote control with you everywhere.

1018
01:10:58,370 --> 01:11:00,414
Scott: You know, and you probably tried to do.

1019
01:11:00,434 --> 01:11:07,730
Scott: the people have tried this home automation where, like, you have an app on your phone that does it and you wire all the lights in your house and like the same kind of system.

1020
01:11:08,352 --> 01:11:13,250
Scott: But those only seem to be popular amongst, you know, like wealthy or very techie type people.

1021
01:11:13,650 --> 01:11:18,270
Rym: They also, they do the Internet of shit problem where they're not secure and they cause problems.

1022
01:11:18,670 --> 01:11:28,250
Rym: The difference between a remote control and that and like an app on a phone is that remote controls are direct and do not leave the boundaries of your house.

1023
01:11:28,270 --> 01:11:28,874
Rym: They're air gap.

1024
01:11:28,915 --> 01:11:30,949
Rym: They're not hackable in any meaningful sense.

1025
01:11:31,550 --> 01:11:33,826
Scott: But as soon as you discussed with the garage door.

1026
01:11:34,451 --> 01:11:35,275
Scott: Yeah, true.

1027
01:11:35,758 --> 01:11:37,870
Rym: But that was just extremely poor design there.

1028
01:11:38,990 --> 01:11:40,137
Rym: But like think about a phone app.

1029
01:11:40,499 --> 01:11:42,330
Rym: It is possible there are phone apps.

1030
01:11:42,490 --> 01:11:45,556
Rym: Like if you had a phone or a smart device that has an I.R.

1031
01:11:45,777 --> 01:11:51,990
Rym: receiver and sender, there were phone apps for those devices or software that would literally make them be a remote control.

1032
01:11:53,851 --> 01:12:02,570
Rym: And with Bluetooth, another thing is it would be possible to have a phone app that is a remote control, but it directly connects to devices without using some cloud service or the Internet.

1033
01:12:02,710 --> 01:12:04,115
Rym: It's not accessible anywhere else.

1034
01:12:04,537 --> 01:12:08,210
Scott: Or even just stays on the LAN in your house and doesn't go to a cloud service.

1035
01:12:09,432 --> 01:12:13,650
Rym: But these things tend to always use cloud services because of, well, mostly bad reasons.

1036
01:12:14,270 --> 01:12:20,810
Scott: People's LANs are, you know, if you make it work on LAN only, everyone's house network is so messed up.

1037
01:12:20,870 --> 01:12:22,769
Scott: You would have so many customer support issues.

1038
01:12:23,811 --> 01:12:27,750
Scott: And then you'd have to help people with networking in their house, like actual networking stuff.

1039
01:12:28,212 --> 01:12:29,590
Scott: You would never survive.

1040
01:12:29,971 --> 01:12:30,211
Scott: Right.

1041
01:12:30,572 --> 01:12:30,732
Rym: Yeah.

1042
01:12:30,752 --> 01:12:40,950
Rym: But I guess the moral of this is that even something as prosaic and simple as the television remote control, which went any remote control like it came in.

1043
01:12:41,050 --> 01:12:52,550
Rym: But even though television went specifically like zoom in on something so specific, it's really important to think about how surprising the changes were that happened around it because of it.

1044
01:12:52,650 --> 01:12:55,590
Rym: Like it changed the way people interact with media.

1045
01:12:55,810 --> 01:13:04,830
